  "prompt": "Why does the RBI increase the repo rate during inflation and decrease it during deflation?",
  "response": "The Reserve Bank of India (RBI), like many central banks, uses the repo rate as a tool to control inflation and manage economic growth. Here's how the mechanism works in different economic scenarios:\n\n### During Inflation:\n\n1. **Control Inflation:** Inflation occurs when the price level of goods and services rises, leading to a decrease in purchasing power. To control inflation, the RBI increases the repo rate.\n\n2. **Cost of Borrowing:** By increasing the repo rate, the cost of borrowing for commercial banks rises. Consequently, banks increase their lending rates to businesses and consumers.\n\n3. **Reduce Money Supply:** Higher interest rates discourage borrowing and spending by consumers and businesses. As a result, the money supply in the economy decreases, leading to reduced consumer spending and investment.\n\n4. **Lower Demand:** With reduced spending power, demand for goods and services decreases, which helps in cooling down inflationary pressures.\n\n### During Deflation:\n\n1. **Stimulate Growth:** Deflation is characterized by falling prices, which may lead to reduced consumer spending as they anticipate even lower prices in the future. It can lead to a slowdown in economic growth.\n\n2. **Cheaper Borrowing:** By decreasing the repo rate, the RBI makes borrowing cheaper for commercial banks. Consequently, banks lower their interest rates for loans to businesses and consumers.\n\n3. **Increase Money Supply:** Lower interest rates encourage borrowing and spending, leading to an increase in the money supply in the economy.\n\n4. **Boost Demand:** With more money in circulation and lower borrowing costs, consumer spending and business investment tend to increase. This helps boost demand for goods and services, contributing to economic growth and countering deflationary trends.\n\nIn summary, the RBI adjusts the repo rate to manage the balance between inflation and economic growth. By increasing the rate during inflation, it aims to reduce spending and control price increases. Conversely, by decreasing the rate during deflation, it encourages spending and investment to stimulate economic activity.",
